Introduction

Background

The data in this report comes from the 2011-2015 American Community Survey 5-year Public Use Microdata Sample. It contains data on Oregon housing units for 15,166 households. There are 16 variables describing the housing unit which are all reported in the appendix. The purpose of this report to:

  1. Investigate whether people living in apartments pay less in electricity than those living in houses and, if so, by how much?
  2. Create a predictive model for household electricity costs in Oregon.

After removing vacant lots, homes with no bedrooms, and the serial number variable, the data set contains 13774 units and 15 variables (Table 1). Electricity costs are higher for houses, on average, than for apartments (Table 2). The median electricity cost for an apartment in Oregon is $70 per month and the median electricity cost for a house in Oregon is $100 per month (Table 2).

Most apartments have electricity bills that are between $0 and $350 per month (Figure 6) while most houses seem to have electricity bills that are between $0 and $425 per month (Figure 6). Apartments with a high number of bedrooms appear to be evenly distributed across the range of electricity costs (Figure 2). On the other hand, the majority of houses with 6 or more bedrooms have a monthly electricity cost over $200 (Figure 1). For houses, monthly electricity cost seems to rise as the number of bedrooms increase until three, after which the electricity cost does not appear to increase with additional bedrooms (Figure 3). Although there are more instances of large household sizes at greater bedroom numbers, the majority of households are under five persons across all bedroom sizes (Figure 3). Apartments seem to follow the same trends as houses in electricity cost and household size but it is hard to say as there are very few apartments with over three bedrooms (Figure 4). With that in mind, it does appear that monthly electricity cost does increase with each additional bedroom up to two bedrooms and larger household sizes are fairly exclusive to large bedroom apartments (Figure 4). Most households are occupied by about 2.5 people for both apartments and houses (Figure 6). Houses generally have more bedrooms than apartments (Figure 5). The initial plots show some indication of non-linearity which should be investigated further. The skewness observed in the plots should not be an issue because of the large sample size (n = 13774, Table 1).

Methods

Sampling

The housing units were sampled using systematic sampling where cases were randomly selected at a regular interval. If a housing unit was selected, a file containing the housing data was added to its corresponding Public Use Microdata Area (PUMA) - a sample within a geographic area containing at least 100,000 people. To answer out two questions of interest, we will use the Student’s T-Test and a Multiple Linear Regression Model:

Students T-Test

The Student’s t-test, first described by William Sealy Gosset in 1908, is used to test a statistical hypothesis when the test-statistic follows a Student’s T-distribution (Student, 1908). The t-test has two assumptions:

  1. Normality - the sample mean should follow a normal distribution (under the Central Limit Theorem, large samples will approximately follow a normal distribution)
  2. Independence - the observations should be independent from each other.

A justification for all assumptions are included in the appendix.

Multiple Linear Regression Model

A multiple linear regression models the relationship between one response variable (monthly electricity cost) and multiple explanatory variables using a straight line (Galton, 1898 and Pearson, 1896). The multiple linear regression model has 5 assumptions:

  1. Linearity - there is a linear relationship between the response and explanatory variables.
  2. Homoskedascity - equal variances.
  3. Normality - the residuals are normally distributed.
  4. Multicolinearity - the independent variables are not highly correlated with each other.
  5. Independence - the observations are independent of each other.

A justification for the assumptions can be found in the appendix.

Results

Do people living in apartments pay less for electricity than those living in houses?

To answer the question of whether people living in apartments pay less in electricity than those living in houses, we must specify a set of models that captures the relationship between household type and monthly electricity cost while controlling for the number of bedrooms and number of occupants in the housing unit.

The following model describes the relationship between monthly electricity cost for a housing unit (\(ELEP_i\)), the number of occupants within the household (\(NP\)), the number of bedrooms in the household (\(BDSP\)) and whether the household is a house or an apartment (\(house_i\) = 1 if house, 0 if apt). The error in the estimate is given by \(\epsilon_i\).

\[ELEP_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1NP + \beta_2BDSP + \beta_3house_i + \epsilon_i\]

Each beta coefficient (\(\beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_3\)) determines the strength of the effect of its corresponding variable (\(NP, BDSP, house_i\)). If \(\beta_3\), the coefficient corresponding to the housing type variable, is equal to 0 then the housing type has no effect on electricity cost and we can conclude that people living in apartments and those living in houses pay the same in electricity when accounting for the homes occupancy and number of bedrooms. To test if \(\beta_3 = 0\), we can use a Student’s T-test.

The hypotheses for our question of interest are as follows:

\(H_0: \beta_3 = 0\) i.e. Houses and apartments have the same electricity costs when controlling for number of bedrooms and occupancy.

\(H_A: \beta_3 > 0\) i.e. Houses have higher electricity costs than apartments when controlling for number of bedrooms and occupancy.

Alternatively, if the effect of the number of bedrooms or the number of occupants depends on the household type, we should account for these interactions. In this case our model would be more complex:

\[ELEP_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1NP + \beta_2BDSP + \beta_3house_i + \beta_4(house_i \times NP) + \beta_5(house_i \times BDSP) + \beta_6(BDSP \times NP) + \epsilon_i\]

  • The three-way interaction between household type, number of bedrooms, and number of occupants is a complex interaction that is hard to interpret and, therefore, it was excluded from the model.

The additional parameters describe the interactions between each variable. People living in houses may have larger household sizes than those living in apartments (\(house_i \times NP\)). People living in houses may also have more bedrooms than those living in apartments (\(house_i \times BDSP\)). Housing units with more bedrooms might have more occupants (\(BDSP \times NP\)). We can compare the more complex model with the simpler model to determine which one better fits our data. Ultimately, it was determined that the simpler model is a better fit to the data and a comparison of the two models can be found in the appendix.

According to our original hypotheses,

\(H_0: \beta_3 = 0\) and \(H_A: \beta_3 > 0\)

We perform a Student’s t-test on the reduced model.

With a p-value of less than 2.2e-16, we reject the null hypothesis that \(\beta_3 = 0\) (Table 3). In other words, housing type does have an effect on monthly electricity cost. With 95% confidence, people who live in houses pay between $15.96 and $22.99 more in electricity per month, on average, than those living in apartments while controlling for the number of bedrooms and the number of occupants in the household (Table 4).

A predictive model for monthly electricity costs in Oregon

To determine the set of models we will consider, we will use best subset selection with the regsubsets() function in R. The regsubsets() function outputs Cp, BIC, RSS, and adjusted \(R^2\), a consensus of these metrics will be found to determine how many parameters to include in the model and regsubsets() will determine which parameters will be included in the model. To validate our model, we will use cross validation by setting aside 20% of the data as a test set. A description of the missing data is included in the appendix.

We create dummy variables for all of the categorical variables: house heating fuel, tenure, year built, presence of persons under 18 in household, and presence of persons over 60 in the household. We use regsubsets() to select the best variables for our model. To determine which of these models would be the best, we can evaluate the plots.

The BIC plot predicts that about 11 variables will be ideal (Figure 11), for the Cp plot – about 17 (Figure 10), for the Adjusted \(R^2\) plot – about 23 (Figure 9), and for the RSS plot – about 15 (Figure 8). To determine the number of variables to include in my model, I found the average number of variables suggested by each of the metrics (\(\frac{11+17+23+15}{4}\) = about 17). The 17 variables that were selected are:

  1. NP - Number of people in household
  2. BDSP - Number of bedrooms
  3. FULP - Fuel cost (yearly)
  4. GASP - Gas cost (monthly)
  5. RMSP - Number of rooms
  6. HAhouse - Housing type
  7. HFL1 - House heating fuel (Utility gas)
  8. HFL3 - House heating fuel (Electricity)
  9. HFL6 - House heating fuel (Wood)
  10. HFL8 - House heating fuel (Other fuel)
  11. TEN1 - Tenure (Owned with mortgage or loan)
  12. TEN4 - Tenure (Occupied without payment of rent)
  13. YBL02 - Year built (1940 to 1949)
  14. YBL03 - Year built (1950 to 1959)
  15. YBL04 - Year built (1960 to 1969)
  16. YBL05 - Year built (1970 to 1979)
  17. YBL06 - Year built (1980 to 1989)

The selected model is described by the following equation:

\[ELEP_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1NP + \beta_2BDSP + \beta_3FULP + \beta_4GASP + \beta_5RMSP +...\] \[..+ \beta_6HA + \beta_7HFL1 + \beta_8HFL3 + \beta_9HFL6 + \beta_{10}HFL8 + \beta_{11}TEN1 +..\]

\[..+ \beta_{12}TEN4 + \beta_{13}YBL02 + \beta_{14}YBL03 + \beta_{15}YBL04 + \beta_{16}YBL05 + \beta_{17}YBL06 + \epsilon_i\] To validate the model, we fit the model using the training data, make predictions with the resulting model on our test data, and calculate the error rate.

R2 RMSE MAE NRMSE
0.2055873 66.22193 45.74311 0.5843149

The mean cost of electricity for the test data is 113.33. The root mean squared error, AKA the average distance between the model predicted values and the observed values, is 66.22. The normalized RMSE, which divides the RMSE by the average cost of electricity for the test data, is 0.584. MAE is the Mean Absolute Error which is the average of the absolute values of the errors. The MAE of 45.74 means that on average, the model predicts a value that is $45.74 less than or greater than the true value. Some of this error may be due to ELEP being “top-coded” meaning that it’s truncated at $999. To assess this, let’s determine how much of the predictions are above the true value:

Residuals.Above.Zero Residuals.Below.Zero
1718 1036

There are 1718 residuals above 0 and 1036 residuals below 0 meaning that about 62% of the models predictions were greater than the “true” value, and 37.5% of the model’s predictions were less than the “true” value. This could be congruent with the claim that the model’s predictions are accurate and the sampling method is the cause of the error. This is a limitation in our model and more precise data collection methods could result in more accurate predictions. Additionally, it appears that the model’s predictions were less accurate for houses than for apartments. This makes sense because there are many more variables to take into account for houses like lot size and the value of the property which were two variables that were discarded for this analysis.

Discussion and Conclusion

The purpose of this report was to:

Investigate whether people living in apartments pay less in electricity than those living in houses and, if so, by how much?

We found that people living in apartments do pay less for electricity. With 95% confidence, people who live in houses pay between $15.96 and $22.99 more in electricity per month, on average, than those living in apartments (PValue = 2.2e-16, T-Test).

Create a predictive model for household electricity costs in Oregon.

The predictive model:

\[ELEP_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1NP + \beta_2BDSP + \beta_3FULP + \beta_4GASP + \beta_5RMSP +...\]

\[..+ \beta_6HA + \beta_7HFL1 + \beta_8HFL3 + \beta_9HFL6 + \beta_{10}HFL8 + \beta_{11}TEN1 +..\]

\[..+ \beta_{12}TEN4 + \beta_{13}YBL02 + \beta_{14}YBL03 + \beta_{15}YBL04 + \beta_{16}YBL05 + \beta_{17}YBL06 + \epsilon_i\] was selected. This model had an MAE value of 45.74 which means that on average, the model predicts a value that is $45.74 less than or greater than the true value. Since the mean cost of electricity for the test data is $113.33, an error of $45.74 is not very good. Some of this error may be due to electricity cost being truncated at $999.

Limitations

The PUMS sample is a subset of the full ACS sample so it is prone to additional sampling error. Estimates that arise from PUMS data will have a greater standard error than estimates from the full ACS dataset. There are some limitations to this analysis. Due to truncated variables, our model’s predictions could be more accurate than our data which could introduce bias into the error metrics. There may have been error introduced by nonresponse bias, missing value imputation, by interviewers or by data entry and processing.

T-test assumptions

Normality

Since the sample size is large (n = 13774, Table 1), we can assume normality under the Central Limit Theorem.

Independence

Since the housing units were sampled randomly using systematic sampling, we can assume that the two samples are independent of one another See page 5 of the PUMS Accuracy Assessment for an in-depth description of the sample design.

Multiple Linear Regression Model Assumptions

## Check MLR assumptions
red_elem <- lm(ELEP ~ HA + BDSP + NP, data = df)

#### Residual Diagnostics ####
elep_diag <- augment(red_elem, df)

Linearity Since my explanatory variables are all nominal categorical variables, the linearity assumption cannot be violated.

Normality

qplot(.fitted, .resid, data = elep_diag, alpha=0.5)

In the .resid vs .fitted plot, there appears to be a violation of the normality assumption since most values are situated above the 0 line, indicating a skew to the right. This violation is not of much concern since the sample size is large. Additionally, it should be noted that the line at the top of the .resid vs .fitted graph, separate from the other points, appears to suggest that our model makes predictions for ELEP that are much higher than they should be. However, the sampling method for ELEP caused the variable to be “top-coded” meaning that it is truncated at $999 and, in this case, the model’s predictions may actually be more accurate than the recorded data. This is something to consider when we create a predictive model and may prove to be a limitation.

Constant Variance

qplot(HA, .resid, data = elep_diag, alpha=0.5)

qplot(BDSP, .resid, data = elep_diag, alpha = 0.5)

qplot(NP, .resid, data = elep_diag, alpha=0.5)

The .resid vs BDSP plot and the .resid vs HA plot appear to meet the constant variance assumption. There may be non-constant variance from left to right in the .resid vs. NP plot, however this may be explained by less observations at high NP values.

Independence Since each household was sampled randomly, it means that we can extend our inference to all households in Oregon that have at least one person, pay for their electricity, and are not group accommodation.

Multicolinearity We check using Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) values.

Lot size (ACR) and property value (VALP) measurements are the only variables with missing values. Lot size has 2560 missing values and property value has 4360. Both property value and lot size are missing exclusively for apartments. About 10% of apartments have measurements for VALP but these apartments are all owned by their tenants. Since lot size is missing for all apartments, it is not useful for predicting monthly electricity cost for apartments. Since the apartments that have measurements for property value are all owned apartments, the property value variable is missing not at random and there is no way to make valid inference using this variable. For these reasons, both property value and lot size will be dropped from the data set. Additionally, the serial number (SERIALNO) variable can be dropped since its an identification variable that is different for every case, having no predictive power.

Validate Model

# required packages:metrics, dplyr

# R^2 formula

RSQUARE = function(y_actual,y_predict){
  cor(y_actual,y_predict)^2 
  }

# Model predicted by best subset
best_sub_mod <- lm(ELEP ~ NP + 
                     BDSP + 
                     FULP + 
                     GASP + 
                     RMSP + 
                     HA + 
                     HFL1 + 
                     HFL3 + 
                     HFL6 + 
                     HFL8 + 
                     TEN1 + 
                     TEN4 + 
                     YBL02 + 
                     YBL03 + 
                     YBL04 + 
                     YBL05 + 
                     YBL06, 
                   data = train)

# Prediction
prediction <- best_sub_mod %>% predict(test)
pred_error <- data.frame(R2 = RSQUARE(test$ELEP, prediction),
                         RMSE = rmse(test$ELEP, prediction),
                         MAE = mae(test$ELEP, prediction),
                         NRMSE = rmse(test$ELEP, prediction)/mean(test$ELEP))
# Error

Description of Variables

  • SERIALNO - a unique record identifier for each housing unit.

  • NP - the number of people living in the house hold (from 0-20).

  • TYPE - the type of unit

    • housing unit
    • Institutional group quarters
    • Non-institutional group quarters

  • ACR - lot size

    • b - not a one-family house or mobile home
    • 1 - less than one acre
    • 2 - one to less than ten acres
    • 3 - ten or more acres

  • BDSP - number of bedrooms

    • bb for NA
    • 0-99

  • BLD - units in structure

    • bb - NA
    • 01 - Mobile home or trailer
    • 02 - one-family house detached
    • 03 - one-family house attached
    • 04 - 2 apartments
    • 05 - 3-4 apartments
    • 06 - 5-9 apartments
    • 07 - 10-19 apartments
    • 08 - 20-49 apartments
    • 09 - 50 or more apartments
    • Boat, RV, van, etc.

  • ELEP - monthly electricity cost

    • bbb - NA
    • Included in rent or condo fee
    • 002 - No charge or electricity not used
    • 003..999 - $3 to $999 (rounded and top-coded)

  • FULP Fuel cost - yearly cost for fuels other than gas and electricity

    • bbbb - NA
    • 0001 - Included in rent or in condo fee
    • 0002 - No charge or these fuels not used
    • 0003..9999 $3 to $9999 (Rounded and top-coded)

  • GASP Gas - monthly cost

    • bbb - NA
    • 001 - Included in rent or in condo fee
    • 002 - Included in electricity payment
    • 003 - No charge or gas not used
    • 004..999 - $4 to $999 (Rounded and top-coded)

  • HFL house heating fuel

    • b - NA
    • 1 - Utility gas
    • 2 - Bottled, tank, or LP gas
    • 3 - Electricity
    • 4 - Fuel oil, kerosene, etc.
    • 5 - Coal or coke
    • 6 - Wood
    • 7 - Solar energy
    • 8 - Other fuel
    • 9 - No fuel used

  • RMSP Number of Rooms

    • bb - NA
    • 00…99 - 0 to 99 Rooms (Top-coded)

  • TEN Tenure

    • b - NA
    • 1 - Owned with mortgage or loan (include home equity loans)
    • 2 - Owned free and clear
    • 3 - Rented
    • 4 - Occupied without payment of rent

  • VALP Property value

    • bbbbbbb - NA
    • 0000001..9999999 - $1 to $9999999 (Rounded and top-coded)

  • YBL - When structure first built

    • bb - NA
    • 01 - 1939 or earlier
    • 02 - 1940 to 1949
    • 03 - 1950 to 1959
    • 04 - 1960 to 1969
    • 05 - 1970 to 1979
    • 06 - 1980 to 1989
    • 07 - 1990 to 1999
    • 08 - 2000 to 2004
    • 09 - 2005
    • 10 - 2006
    • 11 - 2007
    • 12 - 2008
    • 13 - 2009
    • 14 - 2010
    • 15 - 2011
    • 16 - 2012
    • 17 - 2013
    • 18 - 2014
    • 19 - 2015

  • R18 Presence of persons under 18 years in household (unweighted)

    • b - NA
    • 0 - No person under 18 in household
    • 1 - 1 or more persons under 18 in household

  • R60 Presence of persons 60 years and over in household (unweighted)

    • b - NA
    • 0 - No person 60 and over
    • 1 - 1 person 60 and over
    • 2 - 2 or more persons 60 and over
